final project

Introduction

RNA-Seq is a powerful tool for analyzing gene expression profiling. It can effectively detect the expressed genes between different conditions over the genome-wide level. For my project, I am interested in comparing differences in kidney cancer gene expression between white female patients age from 20-60 versus African American female patients age from 20-60. I would use the Bioconductor to analyze the RNA-seq in the HT-seq counts file. # Setting up ## Load in the required packages The libraries required for analysis are loaded in. The library of Limma and Glimma are used for analysis and computation differential expression. The edgeR is for organizing the data into a dataframe. Homo.sapiens is made by Bioconductor that enables comparing the GeneID and other methods of naming.

library(limma)
library(Glimma)
library(edgeR)
library(Homo.sapiens)

Loading the data

To get started with this analysis, download the files from TCGA database on the GDC Data Portal https://portal.gdc.cancer.gov/repository. There will be 30 files loaded into R, and each file representing one patient. The working directory is used to set the location where the files are stored.

    knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir="~/Documents/TRGN510/final_project/" )

The files are stored in a collective location. The first five rows are read as an example and printed as a result. The data has 2 columns, the column on the left side is ENSEMBL GENE ID and the column on the right is the number of counts . THE ENSEMBL GENE ID is in the format: ENS(species)(object type)(identifier). (version) The files do not contain a header, so the column heads are denoted as V1 and V2.

read.delim(files[1], nrow=5, header=FALSE)
##                   V1   V2
## 1 ENSG00000000003.13 4831
## 2  ENSG00000000005.5   19
## 3 ENSG00000000419.11 1415
## 4 ENSG00000000457.12 1095
## 5 ENSG00000000460.15  187

Group the data

The content of each file is combined into one dataframe by using readDGE function, and the location of new combined data is called x. The data is sorted based on the parameter of white vs.African American. EdgeR provides a easy method to perform this with a single command readDGE.

x <- readDGE(files, columns=c(1,2))
## Meta tags detected: __no_feature, __ambiguous, __too_low_aQual, __not_aligned, __alignment_not_unique
class(x)
## [1] "DGEList"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "edgeR"

The dimensions of the dataframe are printed. Each file contains 60487 genes (rows) and have a sample size of 30 people (15 white female and 15 African American female) or 30 columns.

dim(x)
## [1] 60487    30

The code below could help to label all the columns in data frame x according to related files.

samplenames<-colnames(x)
sampleNames

Organizing the data

The samples are grouped based on their race. And the information needs to be associated with the columns of the counts matrix. For the tumor grade, Stage 1 and 2 would be define as low grade, and stage 3 and 4 would be define as high grade.

group <- c(rep("AfricanAmerican",15), rep("White",15))
x$samples$group <- group
tumorgrade <-c("low", "low", "low", "low", "high", "low", "low", "low", "low", "low", "high", "low", "low", "low", "low", "low", "low", "high", "low", "low", "low", "high", "high", "low", "high", "high", "low", "high", "low", "low")
x$samples$tumorgrade <- tumorgrade
x$samples

Since the homo.sapiens package doesnt include the ENSEMBL Gene ID in the format provided by the loaded data, the data should convert using a substitution function. The digits following the decimal are replaced to match the key.

library(gsubfn)

geneid <- gsub("\\.[0-9]*$", "", geneid)

The dataframe genes is used to store gene-level information related to rows of genes. The info we need for this data frame is retrieved from the Homo.sapiens. The GeneIDs are related to the symbol and the chromosome number of each gene. The columns of SYMBOL, TXCHROM, and ENSEMBL gene ID are mixed and couldnt separate in the three columns. But when I did the next step and removed the duplicated genes from our dataset, the SYMBOL, TXCHROM, and ENSEMBL can be separated and shown normally. And all the data and functions are presented and worked successfully in the following steps. I already note this in the Known Issue of README file.

genes <- select(Homo.sapiens, keys=geneid, columns=c("SYMBOL", "TXCHROM"), 
                keytype="ENSEMBL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns

genes <- genes[!duplicated(genes$ENSEMBL),]

Data Pre-processing

Transformation from the raw-scale

My data will be transformed from raw data to the useable form. And we would do the calculation of counts per million(cpm) and log of counts per million (lcpm)

cpm <- cpm(x)
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)

More calculation is shown below. L is the average library size in millions. M is the median of the library size in millions.

L <- mean(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
M <- median(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
c(L, M)
## [1] 86.87360 89.56681

Removing the genes that are lowly expressed

The expressions of some genes are low and its not helpful to do the statistical analysis in a meaningful way. And we found the low expression-genes are in both data groups. So to understand the ratio of these genes, we could run the following lines.

table(rowSums(x$counts==0)==9)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 59807   680

EdgeR package gave an easy way to get rid of these lowly expressed genes.

keep.exprs <- filterByExpr(x, group=group)
x <- x[keep.exprs,, keep.lib.sizes=FALSE]
dim(x)
## [1] 20998    30

It showed the number of genes for interpretation reduced from 60487 to 20998. The raw data versus filtered data is shown in a graphical manner using the following lines of code. The package RColorBrewer contribute to create visually appealing graphs.

lcpm.cutoff <- log2(10/M + 2/L)
library(RColorBrewer)
nsamples <- ncol(x)
col <- brewer.pal(nsamples, "Paired")
## Warning in brewer.pal(nsamples, "Paired"): n too large, allowed maximum for palette Paired is 12
## Returning the palette you asked for with that many colors
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(density(lcpm[,1]), col=col[1], lwd=2, ylim=c(0,0.26), las=2, main="", xlab="")
title(main="A. Raw data", xlab="Log-cpm")
abline(v=lcpm.cutoff, lty=3)
for (i in 2:nsamples){
den <- density(lcpm[,i])
lines(den$x, den$y, col=col[i], lwd=2)
}
legend("topright", samplenames, text.col=col, bty="n")
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
plot(density(lcpm[,1]), col=col[1], lwd=2, ylim=c(0,0.26), las=2, main="", xlab="")
title(main="B. Filtered data", xlab="Log-cpm")
abline(v=lcpm.cutoff, lty=3)
for (i in 2:nsamples){
den <- density(lcpm[,i])
lines(den$x, den$y, col=col[i], lwd=2)
}
legend("topright", samplenames, text.col=col, bty="n")

Normalizing gene expression distribution

For normalization of the data, edgeR provides a great function to help us analyze the data. The resultant values are stored in a dataset called norm.factors.

x<- calcNormFactors(x, method = "TMM")
x$samples$norm.factors
##  [1] 1.0677045 1.1755082 1.1321045 0.6065625 0.8859745 1.0645391 1.1663100
##  [8] 1.1178039 1.0567642 1.1178308 1.1535242 1.1177813 1.1227591 0.8747468
## [15] 0.6091573 1.0964542 0.9830666 1.0758909 1.0717371 1.0436450 0.9512229
## [22] 0.9956307 0.8770367 0.7929302 0.8548798 0.9352151 1.1810664 1.0415226
## [29] 1.0615824 1.1610027

The counts of the first sample are reduced to 5% and the second is increased by 500%

x2 <- x
x2$samples$norm.factors <- 1
x2$counts[,1] <- ceiling(x2$counts[,1]*0.05)
x2$counts[,2] <- x2$counts[,2]*5

The graph below plots the data that is normalized versus non-normalized.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
lcpm <- cpm(x2, log=TRUE)
boxplot(lcpm, las=2, col=col, main="")
title(main="A. Example: Unnormalized data",ylab="Log-cpm")
x2 <- calcNormFactors(x2)

Unsupervised clustering of samples

The MDS plot is a method to visualize the level of similarity and the dissimilarities of individual cases of a dataset. The extent of the differences can give an idea of the expected consequence of the differential expression analysis. The plotMDS function of limma can help us to generate the plot. The distances on the plot would show the action of different categories on this data.

library(limma)
library(Glimma)
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
col.group <- group
levels(col.group) <- brewer.pal(nlevels(col.group), "Set1")
## Warning in brewer.pal(nlevels(col.group), "Set1"): minimal value for n is 3, returning requested palette with 3 different levels
col.group <- as.character(col.group)
col.tumorgrade <- tumorgrade
levels(col.tumorgrade) <- brewer.pal(nlevels(col.tumorgrade), "Set2")
## Warning in brewer.pal(nlevels(col.tumorgrade), "Set2"): minimal value for n is 3, returning requested palette with 3 different levels
col.tumorgrade <- as.character(col.tumorgrade)
col.group <- c("purple","orange")[group]
col.tumorgrade <- c("red","blue")[tumorgrade]
plotMDS(lcpm, labels=group, col=col.group)
title(main="A. Sample groups")
plotMDS(lcpm, labels=tumorgrade, col=col.tumorgrade, dim=c(3,4))
title(main="B. Tumor grade classifications")

The interactive version of this graph can be launched using glimma.

glMDSPlot(lcpm,labels=paste(group, tumorgrade, sep="_"),
          groups=x$samples[,c(2,5)], launch=TRUE)

In the following two plots, it showed the relationship between the mean and variances of the data. By using voom, we can see the first the relationship in first graph before the data is normalized. The effect of normalization can be visualized through the lines of the best fit. To view the differential expression levels, we can generate the following table. (Up-up-regulated genes)

vfit <- lmFit(v, design)
vfit <- contrasts.fit(vfit,contrasts = contr.matrix)
efit <- eBayes(vfit)
plotSA(efit, main="Final model: Mean-variance trend")

Examining the number of differentially expressed genes

T-statistics would show a more stringent definition of significance to be applied to the data. In the table below, it showed there are 3 genes are down-regulated and 4 genes are up-regulated.

summary(decideTests(efit))
##        AfricanAmericanVSWhite
## Down                        3
## NotSig                  20991
## Up                          4

We could use the treat method to do the additional filtering of significant genes. The filter requires genes to have a log-fold change bigger than a predetermined value. In the beginning, I didnt see a lot of significant genes through the default cut-offs. In this situation, we could lower the thresholds to identify the most significant genes with the largest effect size. And I set the lfc to 0.1. Now, there are 4 genes significantly up-regulated and 2 genes significantly down-regulated.

tfit <- treat(vfit, lfc=0.1)
dt <- decideTests(tfit)
summary(dt)
##        AfricanAmericanVSWhite
## Down                        2
## NotSig                  20992
## Up                          4

After the changes of lfc, I got 6 significant gene expression.

de.common <- which(dt[,1]!=0)
length(de.common)
## [1] 6

Now, we can see the names of the genes from the de.common list using the following code:

head(tfit$genes$SYMBOL[de.common], n=30)
## [1] "GSTM1"     "OTOGL"     NA          "LINC01788" NA          NA

The vennDiagram function can be used to visualize the DE genes that associated with two groups of patients.

vennDiagram(dt[,1], circle.col = c("turquoise", "salmon"))

write.fit(tfit, dt, file="results.txt")

AfricanAmerican.vs.White <- topTreat(tfit, coef=1, n=Inf)

Using graphical representations of differential expression results

To summarize the genes, the log foldchange is plot against the log counts per million using the plotMD function.

plotMD(tfit, column=1, status=dt[,1], main=colnames(tfit)[1],
       xlim=c(-8,13))

This plot shows a small subset of up-regulated genes. This could be used as a test to to analyze the difference in regulations of the gene between races.

A more interactive version of this plot can be created using Glimma.

glMDPlot(tfit, coef=1, status=dt, main=colnames(tfit)[1],
         side.main="ENSEMBL", counts = lcpm, groups=group, launch = TRUE)

We could generate a heatmap to see the highest expressed genes. Since my dataset is bigger than the normal dataset used in Vignette, so I chose to use heatmap.plus function. Heatmap.plus is a library can help us create the heatmap for larger datasets.

library(gplots)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:IRanges':
## 
##     space
## The following object is masked from 'package:S4Vectors':
## 
##     space
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
library(heatmap.plus)
AfricanAmerican.vs.White.topgenes <- AfricanAmerican.vs.White$ENSEMBL[1:50]
i <- which(v$genes$ENSEMBL %in% AfricanAmerican.vs.White.topgenes)
mycol <- colorpanel(1000,"blue","white","red")
par(cex.main=0.8,mar=c(1,1,1,1))
heatmap.plus(lcpm[i,], scale="row", labRow=v$genes$SYMBOL[i], labCol=group, col=mycol, cexRow=1,cexCol=0.2, margins = c(8,6), main="HeatMap")

To explain the heatmap, the red area stand for up-regulated genes, the blue area stand for down-regulated genes, and the white area stand for no significant gene expression change.

Gene set testing with camera

loading in the c2 curated gene set.

The c2 curated gene set can be used for analyzing human genes in R. The human_c2_v5p2.rdata file can be downloaded from the Broad Institutes Molecular Signatures Database (MSigDB) collection.

load("human_c2_v5p2.rdata")

And then I checked the first several gene sets within the Homo sapiens c2 curated gene sets. And I got the total number of gene sets within Hs. c2

names(Hs.c2)[1:5]
## [1] "KEGG_GLYCOLYSIS_GLUCONEOGENESIS"              
## [2] "KEGG_CITRATE_CYCLE_TCA_CYCLE"                 
## [3] "KEGG_PENTOSE_PHOSPHATE_PATHWAY"               
## [4] "KEGG_PENTOSE_AND_GLUCURONATE_INTERCONVERSIONS"
## [5] "KEGG_FRUCTOSE_AND_MANNOSE_METABOLISM"
length(Hs.c2)
## [1] 4729

Then I used the ids2indices function to map the gene IDs between the c2 gene sets and the v object. And I also create a contrast matrix that can compare the African American patients data versus the White patients data. The camera function shows a competitive test to check whether the genes in a given set are highly ranked in terms of differential expression relative to genes that are not in the set.

idx <- ids2indices(Hs.c2, rownames(v$genes))
cam.AfricanAmericanVSWhite <- camera(v, idx,design,contrast = contr.matrix[,1])
head(cam.AfricanAmericanVSWhite,5)
##                                     NGenes Direction       PValue       FDR
## CHEN_PDGF_TARGETS                       10      Down 0.0000416868 0.1970535
## REACTOME_RNA_POL_I_PROMOTER_OPENING     42        Up 0.0005139808 0.9996656
## REACTOME_MEIOTIC_SYNAPSIS               53        Up 0.0011834254 0.9996656
## SHARMA_ASTROCYTOMA_WITH_NF1_SYNDROM      2      Down 0.0015167466 0.9996656
## KEGG_RNA_DEGRADATION                    22      Down 0.0016199929 0.9996656

The barcode plot represents the relative enrichment of gene sets among the highly or lowly ranked genes between the African American v.s White female in kidney cancer cases.

barcodeplot(efit$t[,1], index=idx$LIM_MAMMARY_LUMINAL_MATURE_UP,
          index2=idx$LIM_MAMMARY_LUMINAL_MATURE_DN, main="AfricanAmericanVSWhite")
